                "html": `<h1>Month 10, Week 37: Flexbox Layout</h1>
<p>Today we learn how to arrange items on a webpage that stretch and stack automaticallyâ€”like a rubber band that adjusts to any screen size!</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: The Expanding Rubber Band ğŸ§±â†’ğŸ“±</b><br/>
    Imagine a row of boxes on a wide screen (like a TV). When you squeeze the screen (like on a phone), the boxes automatically stack into a column. Flexbox is like that smart rubber band that knows how to organize things without breaking!
</div>

<h3>What is Flexbox?</h3>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h4>ğŸ“¦ Flexbox Container vs. Flex Items</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Container:</b> The parent element with <code>display: flex;</code></li>
        <li><b>Items:</b> The children inside the container</li>
    </ul>

    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;">
        <tr style="background: #4A90E2; color: white;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Property</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">What it does</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Example</th>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>display: flex;</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Turns an element into a flex container</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>.container { display: flex; }</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>flex-direction</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Sets direction of items (row, column)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>flex-direction: row;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>justify-content</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Aligns items along the main axis</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>justify-content: center;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: white;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>align-items</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Aligns items along the cross axis</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>align-items: stretch;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8f9fa;">
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>flex-wrap</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Allows items to wrap to next line</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;"><code>flex-wrap: wrap;</code></td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <div style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 15px; background: #fff3cd; border-radius: 5px;">
        <h5>ğŸ¯ Quick Tip: Main Axis vs. Cross Axis</h5>
        <p>If <code>flex-direction: row</code> â†’ <b>Main Axis = Horizontal</b>, Cross Axis = Vertical</p>
        <p>If <code>flex-direction: column</code> â†’ <b>Main Axis = Vertical</b>, Cross Axis = Horizontal</p>
    </div>
</div>

<h3>Flexbox in Action: Simple Examples</h3>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <h4>Example 1: A Basic Flex Row</h4>
    <pre style='background-color: #36454f; color: #fff; border-radius: 5px; padding: 10px;'>
.container {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    background-color: lightblue;
    padding: 20px;
}

.box {
    width: 80px;
    height: 80px;
    background-color: coral;
    margin: 10px;
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 80px;
    font-weight: bold;
}
    </pre>

